# seasonal adjustment is important for removing variables that might affect employment rates
# variables include changes in weather, school schedules, a global pandemic
# https://www.bls.gov/cps/seasfaq.htm
# we will investigate this further at another time and in possibly another project
# common practice is to use seasonally adjusted rates for monthly trends and changes over long periods of time
# let's filter these out

seasonally_adjusted_df = df[(df['Seasonally Adjusted (Y/N)'] == 'Y') & (df['Status (Preliminary / Final)'] == 'Final')]

'''
I want to see which years had noticeable changes in the size of the labor force. Can help policymakers and industry researchers to take note of the effect on the unemployment rate.
Visualize the percentage change in labor force from the year 1976-2023
'''
# Record the labor force value at the end of a year
# Record the labor force value at the end of the next year
# subtract the difference and calculate the percentage difference
# Record the percentage difference
# repeat for multiple years until the last
# plot the percentage differences on a line graph and visualize

december_data = states_adjusted[states_adjusted['Month'] == 'December']
december_data['% Change'] = december_data['Labor Force'].pct_change() * 100
december_data['% Change'].fillna(0)
december_data.plot(x='Year', y='% Change', ylabel='Percentage Change', kind='line', title='Percentage Changes in Labor Force Size', color='r')
plt.axhline(0, color='k',linestyle='--') # horizontal
plt.annotate(
    'min.',
    xy=(2020, december_data['% Change'].min()),
    horizontalalignment='center',
    verticalalignment='top'
);

# let's use linear regression to see how the labor force and the unemployment rate vary with each other

# define the variables and their response variable
predictors = ['Labor Force']
outcome = 'Unemployment Rate'

# create the model and fit it using the variables and response variables
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(states_adjusted[predictors], states_adjusted[outcome])

# show the intercept and the regression coefficient to 15 decimal places
print(f'Intercept: {model.intercept_:.15f}')
print(f'Coefficient Exposure: {model.coef_[0]:.15f}')

print(0.01 / model.coef_[0])

In[37]:
'''
Given that a random worker is selected from Los Angeles County in 2000, what is the probability that they are unemployed?
'''
la_county = seasonally_adjusted_df[(seasonally_adjusted_df['Area Type'] == 'County') & (seasonally_adjusted_df['Area Name'] == 'Los Angeles County')]
la_county_2000 = la_county[la_county['Year'] == 2000]

# divide the number of unemployed workers in LA County by the total number of LA county workers
probability_unemployed = la_county_2000['Unemployment'].sum() / la_county_2000['Labor Force'].sum()
print(f'The probability of being an unemployed resident of Los Angeles County in 2000 is {probability_unemployed.round(4) * 100} %')

The probability of being an unemployed resident of Los Angeles County in 2000 is 5.41 %

'''
Which counties should receive the most attention for creation of employment opportunities?
What are the top 5 counties for median unemployment rates in 2021 and what were their rates?
'''
# only LA County shows up for seasonally adjusted data, so use entire df for this analysis
counties_only_2021 = df[(df['Area Type'] == 'County') & (df['Year'] == 2021)]

# unique() method returns list in order of appearance
counties_only_sorted = counties_only_2021.sort_values(by=['Unemployment Rate %'], ascending=False)
counties_group = counties_only_sorted.groupby('Area Name')['Unemployment Rate %'].agg('max').sort_values(ascending=False)[:5]

# open the JSON file responsible for producing the plot
from urllib.request import urlopen
import json
with urlopen('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plotly/datasets/master/geojson-counties-fips.json') as response:
    counties_one = json.load(response)

# create chloropleth plot using merged dataframe, JSON file, specify fips for locations and show only California state    
fig = px.choropleth(new_counties, geojson=counties_one, color="Unemployment Rate %",
                    locations="fips", projection="mercator", hover_name='Area Name', hover_data={'fips': False, 'Year': True, 'Unemployment Rate %': ':.1f'})

fig.update_geos(fitbounds="locations", visible=False)
fig.update_layout(margin={"r":0,"t":0,"l":0,"b":0})
fig.show()

# We want to find the standard deviation for each year for the state unemployment rate in California
# label the arrays to include in the plot on the x- and y-axis
x = states['Year'].unique()
y = states.groupby('Year')['Unemployment Rate %'].agg('std')

# create plot figure and axes objects
fig = plt.figure()
ax = plt.axes()

# plot using a dashed line and markers for the figure; adjust x-axis for every 5 years
ax.plot(x, y, linestyle='dashed', marker='o');
ax.set_xticks([1980, 1985, 1990, 1995, 2000, 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020]);
ax.set_xlabel('Years');
ax.set_ylabel('Standard deviation from mean unemployment rate');

Here, we can see how the unemployment rate varied from the mean unemployment rate of that year. Subjectively, the standout years are 1983, 2008, and 2020.

I have grouped the data yearly and calculated the standard deviation for each year, i.e. how far the unemployment rate % values spread out from the average unemployment rate % for that year. We can see that 1983, 2008, and 2020 were particularly variable years for this variability, with 2020 being the most variable. And the 5 most variable years for unemployment rate % are 2020, 2021, 1983, 2008, 1977.

Ideally, I would assume that the powers that be want to keep a small level of variability per year for the unemployment rates to maintain strong economic conditions. The lower the unemployment rate is, the higher the number of employed workers in the labor force, and the more productive the region is.

That being said, California does not exist in a vacuum, and there could be plenty of factors that affect productivity on top of unemployment rates alone.

# I want to plot the top 5 counties with their unemployment rates from the first date to the last date
# all 5 counties will appear on the same plot but in different colors
# from this plot, we can start to make useful assessments of the trends seen

# create a dataframe for the top 5 counties
top_5_counties_df = df[df['Area Name'].isin(counties_group.index)]

# create 5 different dataframes for each county
county_one = top_5_counties_df[top_5_counties_df['Area Name'] == counties_group.index[0]][['Date', 'Unemployment Rate %']]
county_two = top_5_counties_df[top_5_counties_df['Area Name'] == counties_group.index[1]][['Date', 'Unemployment Rate %']]
county_three = top_5_counties_df[top_5_counties_df['Area Name'] == counties_group.index[2]][['Date', 'Unemployment Rate %']]
county_four = top_5_counties_df[top_5_counties_df['Area Name'] == counties_group.index[3]][['Date', 'Unemployment Rate %']]
county_five = top_5_counties_df[top_5_counties_df['Area Name'] == counties_group.index[4]][['Date', 'Unemployment Rate %']]

# sort values in each dataframe for easier plotting
big_data = [county_one, county_two, county_three, county_four, county_five]
[x.sort_values(by='Date', inplace=True) for x in big_data]

# plot the graphs and zoom in on the years 2012-2023
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
ax = plt.axes()
ax.plot(county_one['Date'], county_one['Unemployment Rate %'], color='r', label=counties_group.index[0]);
ax.plot(county_two['Date'], county_two['Unemployment Rate %'], color='g', label=counties_group.index[1]);
ax.plot(county_three['Date'], county_three['Unemployment Rate %'], color='b', label=counties_group.index[2]);
ax.plot(county_four['Date'], county_four['Unemployment Rate %'], color='k', label=counties_group.index[3]);
ax.plot(county_five['Date'], county_five['Unemployment Rate %'], color='c', label=counties_group.index[4]);
ax.set_xlim([datetime(2012, 1, 1), datetime(2023, 1, 1)]);
ax.set_xlabel('Year');
ax.set_ylabel('Unemployment Rate %');
ax.legend();

As shown in the graphs above, all of the top 5 counties have reducing unemployment rates over the last 10 years. We can pay particular attention to Imperial and Mariposa County as it had the largest spike in the early 2020s, presumably due to the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic. More initiatives and programming should be centered and targeted towards Imperial and Colusa Counties to reduce the unemployment levels to pre-pandemic levels.

Another observation that is specifically eye-opening is how quickly these counties have managed to return to pre-pandemic levels of unemployment, again with Imperial and Mariposa Counties being the standout counties whose unemployment rates have dipped below what was observed before the global pandemic.

As a call for further investigation, we should look at the annual spikes in the unemployment rates at the turn of the calendar year. Unemployment rates seem to follow a yearly pattern of decreasing towards the end of Q1, Q2, Q3 and then get subjected to a significant spike at the end of Q4.

From the graphs shown above, we can see that all 5 of the Metropolitan Statistical Areas shown exhibit steady declines in their unemployment rates. Additionally, it's important to note the stark contrast in the unemployment levels in the El Centro Metropolitan Statistical Area when put up against the remaining 4 areas. Government programs to further initiate the creation of jobs in this specific area can help reduce unemployment rates to even lower levels than before.

Simultaneously, looking at all 5 areas, we can note the shift from about 2015 onwards to a slower rate of decrease for the unemployment levels in each Metropolitan Statistical Area before the sharp increase during the COVID-19 pandemic. It only took all 5 of these areas up until 2022 to return to pre-pandemic levels.
